In Memoriam

Celebrating 80 Years of the Eucy

Dear Reader,

In 1940, this school published its first School Annual, the Eucalyptus. It was created to be ‘a permanent embodiment of happy memories and a source of lasting inspiration’ from the graduating class of 1940 to the students and the school. Since then, KIS has been publishing Eucys annually, each year, lighting the torch of inspiration for the next year to continue the Eucy tradition.

The Class of 1940 had created this historical record amidst the anxieties of World War 2. Eighty years later we face a similar darkness of uncertainties. The school was closed in the middle of its second semester; we were unable to say our goodbyes; and classes were taken online across the globe. We currently live under strict curfews and practice various forms of social distancing. Life has taken up a new normal. There was a point at which we were unsure that the Class of 2020 would have a Eucy.

This is where, just as unpredictable as these times have proven, we decided to step in to help the students, and publish this Eucy. We do this to continue the legacy of the Eucy and we do it in support of the Class of 2020. And in true KIS spirit, everyone has responded by contributing photos and messages to help compile this Eucy.

We managed to do the best we could with what we have!

The Eucy has grown over the years to be a symbol of our endurance during trying times since 1940. It remains a testament to our steadfast love for each other and to our concern for the social and emotional wellbeing of our students. It is a reminder of who we are, who we can be, and where we belong.

Dear Class of 2020, I present to you the 80th edition of the Eucalyptus. I hope you will always carry your time here in Kodai close to your hearts. These are the memories you will hold during your worst of days and best. Use these memories to remain an inspiration to those around you and to your juniors.

This is our gift to you. #supportClassof2020

Yours Truly,

Manjusha Ninan

Contributors: The KIS community

Dear Class of 2020,

Usually, in most typical years, we say goodbye to the graduating class and their families all at once. We have a church service, a lavish banquet, a commencement ceremony—you have a non-school-related strictly-off-premises parent-supervised after-graduation party—and that’s about it.

This has not been a typical year.

Thankfully, you are not a typical class.

I’m going to say it: you are the most academically accomplished class in the 119- year-history of KIS (with the possible exception of the Class of 1986). You won’t have IB exam scores to prove it, because there won’t be IB exams this year, but the truth remains. You are a smart and close-knit group, and that has helped you—and frankly the rest of us—get through this year’s adversity with love, grit and compassion. Thank you.

As I write this most of you have left Kodai, while some of you, stranded by circumstance, remain here at school. In any case, know that wherever you are and wherever you go there will always be a part of KIS that stays with you.

More than your school success, I am eager to see what each one of you makes of yourself in life. Above all, I want you to be good and thoughtful people. I take pride and feel joy as I read the words of a member of the Class of 2020 to his teachers and mentors on his departure from Kodai: “Coming to….KIS, where

my ideas were encouraged and improved on, has been an unparalleled journey…Thank you for impacting my life in a way that has made a difference….keep me in your prayers so that I

am able to be a student and a citizen that the world needs.”

Will do.

Until we meet again,

Mr. Corey

Principal

Kodaikanal International School
